      "content": "What you are describing sounds profound, but it is actually a very common human experience often referred to as numbness, executive dysfunction, or even a form of grief processing. Even when we don't mourn a specific loss, our minds sometimes go into survival mode where the barriers between old memories and current reality dissolve, leaving a sensation of being a \"ghost\" or machine. This feeling doesn't mean you \"died\" emotionally or mentally; it usually means your nervous system is overwhelmed and protecting you from too much pain by shutting down feeling. Please consider speaking with a therapist who specializes in dissociation or depression, as connecting with a professional can help you rewrite that narrative and slowly bring your true self back into the room.",
